# Development Notes

## Project Purpose

Automated Project Tracker was built to function like a lightweight project management app inside Microsoft Excel.

The goal was to create a reusable workbook that helps users manage projects, tasks, notes, and release progress without needing a separate subscription-based tool.

This project was designed as more than a static spreadsheet. It uses structured layouts and Excel automation to create a guided project tracking workflow.

---

## Development Approach

The workbook was built around a dashboard-first structure.

The dashboard acts as the main control center where users can view projects, create new projects, and navigate to project workspaces. Each project workspace is designed to follow a consistent format so users can manage different projects in the same way.

The main development focus was to keep the workbook:

- Easy to understand
- Organized
- Reusable
- Beginner-friendly
- Useful for real project work
- More automated than a basic spreadsheet

---

## Workbook Structure

The workbook includes multiple organized areas for project management.

Key areas include:

- Main dashboard
- Project list
- Project workspace sheets
- Task tracking sections
- Notes and brainstorming areas
- Release notes
- Version/release logs
- Supporting workbook instructions

The structure was designed so users can separate project-level information while still managing everything from one central workbook.

---

## Excel Tables

Excel tables were used to keep project data organized and easier to expand.

Tables help support:

- Structured data entry
- Consistent headers
- Cleaner filtering and sorting
- Easier references for automation
- Expandable project records

Using tables also helps reduce the chance of layout issues when users add more rows of project data.

---

## VBA Automation

VBA was used to support the automated parts of the workbook.

The automation was designed to help users complete common project tracking actions without needing to manually duplicate sheets, rebuild layouts, or manage the workbook structure themselves.

Automation supports workflow areas such as:

- Creating project workspaces
- Updating project records
- Managing project tracker sections
- Supporting release/version logging
- Improving navigation and usability

The goal was to keep the technical work behind the scenes while giving the user a simpler front-end experience.

---

## Project Creation Workflow

One of the main workbook features is the ability to create a new project from the dashboard.

The project creation workflow was designed so the user can enter project information and generate a dedicated workspace for that project.

This helps prevent users from needing to manually copy sheets, rename tabs, or rebuild tracker sections.

The purpose of this workflow is to make the workbook feel more like an Excel-based application than a basic template.

---

## Dashboard Design

The dashboard was designed to give users a quick view of their active projects and project status.

The dashboard layout focuses on:

- Clear project visibility
- Simple navigation
- Organized project summaries
- A cleaner visual structure
- Easy access to project workspaces

The dashboard was adjusted during development to support expandable project lists while keeping the top summary sections stable.

---

## Project Workspace Design

Each project workspace was designed to give users one place to manage the details of a specific project.

The project workspace includes areas for tasks, notes, brainstorming, release planning, and version history.

The layout was built to keep related project information together instead of scattering it across different files or tools.

---

## Release and Version Tracking

The release/version tracking section was included to support projects that evolve over time.

This feature is useful for users building apps, spreadsheets, creative projects, business tools, or any project that may go through multiple releases.

The release tracking workflow helps users document:

- Version names
- Release dates
- Completed releases
- Release notes
- Older release history

This was included because project progress often happens in stages, and users need a way to look back at what changed over time.

---

## Notes and Logs

Notes and logs were included so users can keep project context inside the workbook.

These areas are intended for:

- Daily notes
- Older notes
- Ideas
- Decisions
- Brainstorming
- Progress updates
- Future improvements

This supports users who want both task tracking and project journaling in one place.

---

## User Experience Goals

The workbook was designed for users who may not be advanced Excel users.

The user experience goals were:

- Make the workbook easy to navigate
- Reduce manual setup
- Keep sections clearly labeled
- Avoid unnecessary complexity
- Use buttons and structured areas where possible
- Make the workbook feel approachable

Although the workbook uses VBA and automation, the user should not need to understand the code to use the product.

---

## Testing and Refinement

The workbook was tested through repeated project creation, task entry, release tracking, and sample data workflows.

Testing focused on:

- Creating new projects
- Checking dashboard updates
- Entering task data
- Using notes sections
- Recording release/version information
- Reviewing workbook layout consistency
- Preparing screenshots and demo video content

The workbook was also reviewed from a customer perspective to make sure the product included enough instructions, visual examples, and support files for a digital download.

---

## Digital Product Packaging

Automated Project Tracker was prepared as a digital product for Etsy.

The product package includes the workbook and a README file to help users understand what is included and how to get started.

Product preparation included:

- Workbook cleanup
- Sample screenshots
- Demo video
- README creation
- ZIP file packaging
- Etsy listing images
- Store description
- Product preview review

This helped turn the workbook from a personal project into a customer-ready digital product.

---

## Lessons Learned

This project helped reinforce several important development lessons:

- A useful Excel product needs both functionality and clear presentation.
- Automation is most valuable when it removes repetitive setup work for the user.
- Dashboard layout matters because users need to understand the workbook quickly.
- Digital products need documentation, screenshots, and trust-building details.
- A case study can show the value of a product without giving away the paid file.

